Typcially, things scale best when you avoid allocations. ADO.Net still wants you to allocate new SqlConnection (or OleDbConnection, MySqlConnection, OdbcDbConnection, etc) objects for most requests to the database so it can do Connection Pooling properly, but otherwise you want your BL/DL layers to be mainly either static, singleton, single global, or HTTP response-scoped, and there are arguments for each of those options depending on the situation.

In other words, we want this:

    public DL
    {
        private static string connectionString = &quot;...&quot;;

        public static IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; GetAll&lt;T&gt;() 
        {
             using (var cn = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
             {
                 cn.Open():
                 //...
             }
        }
    }

rather than this:

    public DL
    {
        //Assume this is disposed properly for simplicity...
        // Maybe a winforms app with fewer longer cycles, rather than a web app with lots of threads or AppDomains
        private static SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(&quot;...&quot;);

        public static IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; GetAll&lt;T&gt;() 
        {
            connection.Open();
            //...
            connection.Close();
        }
    }

or this:

    public DL 
    {
        private SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(&quot;...&quot;);

        public IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; GetAll&lt;T&gt;() 
        {
             connection.Open();
             //...
        }
    }

or even this:

    public DL : IDisposable
    {
        private SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(&quot;...&quot;);

        public IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; GetAll&lt;T&gt;() 
        {
             connection.Open();
             //...
        }
  
        public void Dispose()
        {
             if (connection is IDisposable) connection.Dispose();
        }
    }

ADO.Net wants the connection objects scoped entirely to the individual API methods that actually call to the database, rather than a single connection for the whole data layer. As bad as the allocations are, the security/authentication/connection negotiations with the database server are typically much worse. Re-using the connection object optimizes for saving that little bit of memory at the expense of much worse efficiency actually accomplishing the connections with the database.

Aside from connections, though, we want to limit needing to create new instances of anything. Sometimes, even my &quot;business objects&quot; are just static mappings over `IDataRecord`, where I don&#39;t need to allocate new instances separate from the DTO returned by ADO.Net. But right now I&#39;m mainly looking at the `DL` and `BL` manager types, and here that means either `static` methods (maybe even the full class) or some mechanism for sharing a common instance, be it singleton, global, or other.

**BOTH of the options in the question fail at this.**

But as for the specific question, let&#39;s look at whether the first option needs to implement `IDisposable` or not.

If the data layer is built such that there is no connection object stored in the class instance itself, but rather connections are created, opened, and disposed within the scope of each API method, then the data layer object probably has no unmanaged fields property members at all, and therefore _does not need to implement the `IDisposable` pattern._ If the data layer does not implement `IDisposable`, then it&#39;s also safe to create the throw-away instances as seen in the first example. Moreover, the business layer also probably doesn&#39;t need to implement `IDisposable`.

Moving on to the second option.

This option does not quite properly understand `IDisposable`. It _does_ follow the documentation patterns correctly, but the documentation is misleading here, in that it provides the complete/long version of the pattern that includes finalizers. You only need to write a finalizer if you&#39;re building a brand new kind of unmanaged resource from scratch. If you&#39;re not writing your own finalizer, but only wrapping something else that&#39;s IDisposable, you can almost certainly get by with a simplified version of the pattern.

In a BL/DL situation, the only unmanaged resource is typically a database connection somewhere down the way (maybe not even that, if everything is hidden behind a HTTP/JSON API). The database connection will have an ADO.Net provider that&#39;s already done the finalizer; you don&#39;t need to write your own. Now you&#39;re to the point where `Dispose()` _always_ just calls `Dispose(true)`, and nothing else ever calls `Dispose(false)`. Additionally, nothing else ever looks at `disposedValue`, and the `data` variables, which do follow the complete pattern, and are therefore all safe to call `Dispose()` multiple times. 

In other words, the complicated pattern with the overloaded method, boolean flag, and conditional blocks is no longer needed. You can have a simple `public void Dispose() {data.Dispose();}`

But again, that&#39;s predicated on `BL` instances maintaining an instance of the `DL`, where a static or similar option may be better in the first place.

